s era, from elite yangban women to women who were enslaved. Women are shown to have used various strategies to seek status, economic rights, and more comfortable spaces, with some women even emerging as Confucian intellectuals and exemplars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aWomen in ConfucianismzKoreaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aAsian Studies : Korean Studies. 4aHistory : History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aJi-Young, Jung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Youngmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Youngmin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPettid, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPettid, Michael J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSoonGu, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438437774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438437774/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles